          Intro - Introduces the Utilities Disk #1 contents

     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          The _U_t_i_l_i_t_i_e_s _D_i_s_k #_1(U1) contains several programs that
          perform a variety of tasks.  Some of the programs are unique
          to the Model 4/4D/4P environment while others are based on
          programs available in other operating systems, such as the
          BSD *NIX operating system, which was developed at the
          University of California at Berkeley.

          Here are some brief descriptions of programs included on
          _U_t_i_l_i_t_i_e_s _D_i_s_k #_1:

          _L_o_o_k Can determine the format of a diskette made by many
               different operating systems.  For LDOS 5, TRSDOS 6, and
               LS-DOS 6 disks, _l_o_o_k(U1) will show the location of each
               file on the disk.

          _M_a_p_m_e_m
               Displays information on the utilization of memory, and
               gives meaningful names to the memory modules it
               locates.

          _M_o_r_e A very powerful utility for displaying the contents of
               text files.  Allows you to examine groups of files with
               searching and skipping capabilities.  The output of
               most of the programs on the _U_t_i_l_i_t_i_e_s _D_i_s_k #_1 can be
               directly routed through _m_o_r_e(U1).  Based on the BSD
               _m_o_r_e command.

          _L_s   Displays the contents of directories in a wide variety
               of formats.  Based on the BSD _l_s command.

          _O_o_p_s Allows you to edit commands typed at the DOS command
               prompt.  Provides the same editing commands as found in
               BASIC.

          _W_c   Scans through one or more files and computes the number
               of characters, words and lines of text that are
               present.  Based on the BSD _w_c command.

          _X_l_r_8_s_e_t
               For systems with XLR8er adapters, this program applies
               a series of patches when the system boots, rather that
               placing them permanently in the operating system.  The
               patches included are 1/5th the size of the original
               Houde patches.







